x4freetext: n-TOF facility, CERN. High intensity pulsed proton
beam, repetition rate 0.4 Hz, proton pulse width of
Spallation reaction of fast protons on the
Neutron flux was evaluated using long-term measurements
with several detectors and Monte Carlo simulations. The
uncertainty in the neutron flux is 2% below 10 keV and
above 100 keV, and 4%-5% between 10 and 100 keV neutron
energy. In the investigated neutron energy range the
beam interception factor never changed by more than
+-1.5% compared to the value at 4.9 eV.
C6D6 detector system was installed perpendicular to
the neutron beam and about 9 cm upstream from the
capture sample. Detectors were calibrated at 0.662,
Dependence of the detection efficiency on gamma-ray
energy and the effect of the gamma-ray threshold of
250 keV were corrected using the pulse height weighting
technique, providing a measure for the absolute neutron
For the energy dependence of neutron flux up to 150 keV
B-10(n,a) and Li-6(n,a) standard c-s were used,
U-235(N,F) standard c-s - at higher energies.
4.9 eV resonance was used for absolute neutron flux
The normalization factor was determined via the
saturated resonance technique in an additional run with
Au sample of the same size as the Ni sample.
- by runs with an empty PEEK container,
- with a 62Ni sample of the same diameter,
TOF spectra were corrected for dead-time effects.
The background due to oxygen is negligibly small.
Additionally, the neutron capture yield has been
measured with a set of neutron filters (W,Mo,Al)located
about 50 m upstream of the sample.

63-Ni sample was produced by irradiating highly
enriched 62-Ni in a thermal reactor, irradiation time
> 20 years. 63Cu impurity has been chemically separated
prior to the measurement. By means of mass spectrometry
the 63Ni/62Ni ratio in the sample was determined to be
0.123 +- 0.001, the contribution from other Ni isotopes
was found to be < 1%. 1156 mg NiO powder were
encapsulated in a thin-walled cylinder made of PEEK
(polyether ether ketone, net mass 180 mg) to produce a
sample of 20 mm diameter, 2.2 mm thickness.
